Digital Arbitrage Tooling (DAT)
Documentation Master Plan (Aligned to NS‑GGP Canonical Template)
PurposeThis document defines the authoritative documentation master plan for DAT, strictly aligned to the existing NS‑GGP document structure (000–014).
DAT is an execution engine. It converts approved opportunities into market actions (listings, pricing, sourcing, routing). DAT never governs itself; it executes within constraints defined by GGP and informed by PIE / SIG / SIM.
This master plan ensures:
DAT documentation mirrors GGP structurally
Execution risk is auditable
Automation never bypasses governance

DAT Documentation Index (Canonical)

NS‑DAT‑000 — CHARTER
Purpose: Define why DAT exists
Scope:
Mission of DAT
Why execution must be systematized
DAT’s role in the NS engine ecosystem
Explicit non‑goals (governance, accounting, identity)
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑000

NS‑DAT‑001 — OVERVIEW
Purpose: High‑level conceptual framing
Scope:
What DAT executes (arbitrage, listings, pricing actions)
Execution surfaces (marketplaces, channels)
Relationship to PIE (insights) and GGP (authorization)
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑001

NS‑DAT‑002 — TAXONOMY
Purpose: Define DAT’s atomic execution components
Scope:
Opportunity
Execution Plan
Action Step
Channel
Constraint
Execution Result
These primitives define how execution is reasoned about.
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑002

NS‑DAT‑003 — ARCHITECTURE
Purpose: Logical execution architecture
Scope:
Opportunity intake
Plan generation
Channel adapters
Execution workers
Result collection
Logical design only (not infra).
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑003

NS‑DAT‑004 — LIFECYCLE
Purpose: End‑to‑end execution lifecycle
Scope:
Opportunity receipt
Authorization check (GGP)
Plan instantiation
Action execution
Outcome reporting
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑004

NS‑DAT‑005 — DECISION
Purpose: Execution decision semantics
Scope:
When DAT may execute automatically
When human confirmation is required
Abort / rollback decisions
All execution decisions are bounded by GGP policy.
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑005

NS‑DAT‑006 — VERSION
Purpose: Execution plan versioning
Scope:
Versioning of execution plans
Changes due to channel differences
Impact of plan updates mid‑execution
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑006

NS‑DAT‑007 — DATAMODEL
Purpose: Persistence and execution data contracts
Scope:
Execution plans
Execution attempts
Results and errors
Replay safety
Mirrors: NS‑GGP‑007

NS‑DAT‑008 — EEE (End‑to‑End Example)
Purpose: Validate execution logic
Scope:
Insight from PIE
Approval via GGP
Execution via DAT
Feedback loop to PIE and FLO
